Yes, if you throw a *plain value*, rather than a `new Error`, that situation can occur:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    try {
      throw undefined;
    } catch(e) {
      console.log(e, typeof e);
    }


    try {
      throw null;
    } catch(e) {
      console.log(e, typeof e);
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

But this is very bad practice - better to wrap a thrown error in `new Error` (or another of the appropriate error constructors):

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    try {
      throw new Error(&#39;error!&#39;);
    } catch(e) {
      console.log(e);
      console.log(e.stack);
      console.log(e.name);
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Yes, if the code throw a custom exception, for example: 

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    try {
      throw &quot;this is a string exeption&quot;;
    } catch(e) {
      console.log(e);
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

But also, it is possible to:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    try {
      throw undefined;
    } catch(e) {
      console.log(e);
    }

    try {
      throw null;
    } catch(e) {
      console.log(e);
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Probably in the custom code a custom exception with fields data field is used, and therefore you want to be sure you are catching the right custom exception and not a normal JS exception

